<post author="MikeConnolly" timestamp="May 24, 2013 3:22 AM">
<s>doing a little bit of looking into alternatives to captcha: 
option 1: field added using js to form 
add a checkbox field to your form, but not by conventional means of adding <input type="checkbox" name="field" >; but by adding the field using javascript. 
</s><s>this would meain spambots trawling a website looking for form's and their inputs, won't see the field setup in the javascript. 
</s><s>if this field was flagged as 'mandatory' on the web form, question i have is; is that field marked as mandatory by the form handler "formprocessv2.aspx"? 
</s><s>or as i suspect, does setting a field as 'mandatory' only add the relevant js validation to the html code?</s><s> therefore, this solution may rely on the form-handler being changed to reject entries without mandatory fields submitted. 
</s><s>option 2: honeypot 
</s><s>delibrately add a random field to a form that is hidden using css, but will be submitted by spambots which don't realise that the field is actually redundant. 
</s><s>this would mean the form handler rejecting any form submission made with the hidden field completed. 
</s><s>this would be similar to the current 'anti-bot' field at present, but work's in reverse; submission of the hidden field reveals source as only a "spambot". 
</s><s>therefore could filter out human over spambot entry. 
</s><s>at present, a hidden field can be submitted using anti-bot module; but over time spambots become educated on the range of hidden fields and their possible values. 
</s><s>but i suppose, in the reverse too; spambots will learn the range of hidden fields not to submit. 
</s></post>
</TEXT>
</DOC>


